{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 15:43:20.306637", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — SDN spine–leaf lab\nDate/time: (session time)\n\nSummary / impact\n- Network anomaly detected: inter-host connectivity on the 10.0.0.0/24 tenant subnets is failing. Pings between same-subnet and between different subnets return \"Destination Host Unreachable\" and show 100% loss.\n- The failure is localized to the data-plane switching components (Open vSwitch bridges/daemon) on the OVS switches (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1). The management interfaces (20.0.0.0/24) remain configured and show some traffic.\n- Root cause: the Open vSwitch service (openvswitch-switch) is not running / OVS bridge device (ovs-system) is DOWN on the switches, so host frames are not being forwarded at the switch data plane.\n\nKey evidence collected\n1) End-host ping tests\n- host_1_1 -> host_1_2 (same /24) failed:\n  - Ping output: \"From 10.0.0.1 icmp_seq=1 Destination Host Unreachable\" then 100% packet loss.\n  - Similar behavior for host_1_1 -> host_2_1 and other host-to-host pings; all returned Destination Host Unreachable from the source and 100% loss.\n\nInterpretation: the source host's kernel is unable to forward ARP/ICMP to the destination (no Layer-2 connectivity/bridge forwarding), so the kernel generates the unreachable.\n\n2) Host network configuration (examples)\n- host_1_1: eth0 up, inet 10.0.0.1/24, route 10.0.0.0/24 dev eth0.\n- host_1_2: eth0 up, inet 10.0.0.2/24.\n- host_2_1: eth0 up, inet 10.0.0.9/24.\n\nInterpretation: host IP and routing configuration are correct; lack of reachability is not due to missing host IPs/routes.\n\n3) Switch interface/bridge state\n- leaf_1 ip output shows:\n  - \"ovs-system: ... state DOWN\"\n  - \"leaf_1: flags=4098<BROADCAST,MULTICAST> ... state DOWN\"\n  - physical ports (eth0..eth12) appear UP and many are \"master ovs-system\", but the bridge/ovs-system device is DOWN.\n  - Per-interface stats: eth0..eth3 show RX packets but TX packets 0 on the switch side.\n\n- leaf_2 ip output shows the same pattern: ovs-system and leaf_2 bridge state DOWN, eth interfaces UP.\n\n- spine_1 ip output also shows \"ovs-system: ... state DOWN\" and the management interface (eth8) has 20.0.0.1 configured.\n\nInterpretation: PHY links to hosts and other switches appear up at the NIC level (ethX show UP), but the OVS bridge itself (ovs-system / logical switch device) is down, so no L2 switching/forwarding is happening despite link presence.\n\n4) Open vSwitch service state\n- leaf_1 systemctl status openvswitch-switch:\n  - \"openvswitch-switch.service ... Active: inactive (dead)\"\n\nInterpretation: the Open vSwitch daemon/service on at least leaf_1 is stopped/inactive. That explains why ovs-system and the OVS bridge devices are DOWN and forwarding is not functioning. (We did not show systemctl outputs for leaf_2/spine_1, but their ovs-system devices are DOWN as shown above — consistent with OVS service not running.)\n\nPutting it together — anomaly localization and root cause\n- Symptom: Hosts cannot reach each other on 10.0.0.0/24 (and cross-leaf traffic). ICMP attempts return Destination Host Unreachable generated by the source.\n- Localized devices: leaf_1, leaf_2, and spine_1 (the OVS instances on those switches).\n- Root cause (most likely): Open vSwitch (openvswitch-switch) is not running on the switches, causing the ovs-system bridge(s) to be DOWN. Because the OVS logical bridges are down, the physical NICs are not being bridged/forwarded at Layer 2, so host frames are received at the NIC but not forwarded — resulting in ARP/ICMP failure and \"Destination Host Unreachable\" at the source.\n\nAdditional observations\n- Management plane (20.0.0.0/24) IPs are present on switch management interfaces (e.g., leaf_1 eth12 = 20.0.0.5, leaf_2 eth12 = 20.0.0.6, spine_1 eth8 = 20.0.0.1). There is RX/TX activity on the management interfaces, indicating the control/management network is at least partially functional.\n- The problem is not a simple host misconfiguration (hosts have correct IPs and kernel routes) and is not explained by physical link down (eth interfaces on switches show UP). The data-plane forwarding element (OVS bridge/daemon) is the failing component.\n\nRecommended next information to gather (for confirmation; no remediation proposed here)\n- openvswitch-switch service status and logs (journalctl) on leaf_2 and spine_1 to confirm service state and failure cause.\n- ovs-vsctl show (or equivalent) on the switches to see bridge configuration and ports when service starts/stops.\n- Controller connectivity/state (if relevant) — although the immediate root cause is local OVS service inactivity, controller reachability/logs may be useful to see if controller-driven changes preceded the outage.\n\nConcluding statement\n- The network health is degraded: tenant L2/L3 forwarding is non-functional due to OVS data-plane/daemon being down on the switches (leaf_1/leaf_2/spine_1). The most direct, evidence-backed root cause is the Open vSwitch service being inactive, leaving the ovs-system bridge(s) DOWN and preventing host-to-host traffic forwarding.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 25322, "output_tokens": 2425, "total_tokens": 27747, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 25216}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1152}}}
